1. Operating System & Time Libraries (Standard Python)

    Library: os
        Definition: A built-in tool to interact with the computer's file system and folders.

        Usage: Used via os.getcwd() to automatically figure out the exact folder path where
                the script is currently running. This ensures downloaded files are saved exactly
                in the project folder, rather than getting lost in the computer's default "Downloads" directory.

    Library: time
        Definition: A built-in tool to handle time-related tasks.

        Usage: Used via time.sleep(1) to force the script to freeze and do absolutely nothing
                for a specific number of seconds. This is a basic, rigid way to wait for webpage elements to process.

2. Selenium Core Libraries (The Automation Engine)

    Class: webdriver.Chrome
        Definition: The main robot engine that physically opens and controls the Google Chrome browser.

        Usage: Assigned to self.driver, it acts as the central command hub to open websites
                (.get()) and execute automated actions on the internet.

    Class: Service
        Definition: A background manager that starts and stops the chromedriver.exe file.

        Usage: Tells the script exactly where the driver executable is located on the hard
                drive so the browser can launch successfully.

    Class: Options
        Definition: A configuration tool to change how the browser behaves before it even opens.

        Usage: Used here for two critical tasks: blocking the annoying "search engine choice
                screen" popup, and forcefully changing the browser's default download folder to the script's current directory.

3. Selenium Synchronization Libraries (The Waiting Logic)

    Class: WebDriverWait
        Definition: A smart waiting tool. Instead of pausing blindly for a fixed time,
                    it waits intelligently up to a maximum time limit, moving forward the exact
                    millisecond the required item appears.

        Usage: Used extensively to pause the script until specific text boxes or buttons are
                fully loaded and ready to be interacted with, preventing crashes caused by slow internet.

    Module: expected_conditions (imported as EC)
        Definition: A set of predefined rules that WebDriverWait uses to know exactly what to wait for.

        Usage: Used specifically as EC.visibility_of_element_located to strictly verify that a web
                element is not just hidden in the background code, but actually physically visible
                on the screen before trying to click or type into it.

    Class: By
        Definition: A set of locator strategies (like a map compass) used to find elements on a webpage.

        Usage: Used exclusively in this script to target elements by their exact HTML ID attribute.

4. The Custom Architecture (WebAutomation Class)

    Method: __init__
        Definition: The initial setup phase that runs automatically the moment the robot is created in memory.

        Usage: Prepares the browser settings, establishes the specific download path, starts the
                driver service, and launches the blank browser window.

    Method: login
        Definition: A custom action sequence specifically for authentication.

        Usage: Forces the browser to the login page, waits for the username and password boxes
                to appear, types the credentials, and executes a click on the login button.

    Method: fill_form
        Definition: A custom action sequence for data entry.

        Usage: Bypasses fragile UI menus by navigating directly to the /text-box URL, waits for
                the form to load, fills in the required text fields, and executes a click on the submit button.

    Method: download
        Definition: A custom action sequence designed to trigger a file download.

        Usage: Attempts to find a sidebar menu item (item-7), clicks it, waits for the
                actual download button to appear on the new page, and clicks it to pull
                a file into the local folder.

    Method: close
        Definition: The final shutdown sequence.

        Usage: Uses self.driver.quit() to completely destroy the browser window, sever
        the connection, and clear it from the computer's memory.